Dear Adrienne, I have decided to start doing yoga after a long (winter) break. I got really excited that you've created this new 30 - Day series! I did my first session yesterday and... I just felt so happy! My body remembered how good it feels! And when I finished the song "I can see clearly" came on my playlist! How awesome is that? I went to the kitchen to reward myself with a nice cup of coffee, I felt warm floor under my feet, birds were singing and... I just felt so grateful! I caught myself hugging my coffee jar with a big smile on my face, haha. 
Then I woke up this morning (crazy 8 o'clock on Sunday!) and I have decided for the first in my life to the practice yoga first thing in the morning. I always feel SO stiff in the morning that I never thought it would be possible without pain. First of all I kind of enjoyed this groggy/sleepy feeling without many thoughts in my head, which helped me concentrate on my breath. And then... I just trusted myself, this new experience, my body, trusted you and went for it! It was amazing! I feel so happy and energised the whole day! I don't know if I can still do it in the morning during the work week but at least I know this is gonna be my weekend treat from now on! I just wanted to say big thank you. You are not only an amazing teacher but such a wonderful positive person! I wonder if you realise how many people get on this mat every day just because of you! 
Lots of love from London!

PIGEON POSE QUESTION FOR OLD TIGHT HIPS!:
Let's use left leg back and right foot folded in pigeon for this example.  (note that I know very little about yoga)
In the correct position, but I seem to have 2 VERY different options, depending on how I shift my weight.
I can either:
1. Sit on left hip, and my body is aligned fairly straight
or
2. Sit more on my right bun (which allows me to be more "on the mat"), but my body is quite askew (bent to right of mat and not an aligned body)

Which would be more "ideal", if I have to choose one?
They are definitely different, but is one more like the eventual goal of pigeon?  I'm not sure what the pigeon is supposed to challenge or stretch, so maybe that info would be helpful?

Day 2 - At the beginning of the lesson, I noticed this urge to move faster, power through. So I suppose that's why I was saying to myself that this is enough, trusting in this being enough.  I was much more aware of my breath in today's practice. I also noticed the tension in parts of my body more today but as the lesson progressed I felt less of the urge to do something about it like an extra stretch here and there.  Post lesson I feel my chest open and core stronger, my breath is less shallow. Could it be that the lesson was stronger than it felt? Well thanks, Adrienne and Benji, looking forward to the next.
Hi Adrian, great start of the day! Hi Benji!

Thank you so much Adriene for making all these videos. I discovered your channel about 2 years ago, but this is the first time that I'm trying to keep up with the challenge according to the correct schedule (earlier I finished 1 video a day and then an other the next day, but then it took days or weeks to get back on the mat, and it's weird because it's only hard to get on the mat, but after that it always feels so good). I've been taking other types of exercise for 8 years now, but yoga is something very different. I really appreciate the stretch and the meditation part of it, it helped me to kind of 'heal, reconstruct' or just strengthen the parts of my body that were kind of destroyed and neglected while doing the other sports or while sitting all day long or standing with the wrong core position. I think the best changes that I realized on my body that were brought by your videos were my shoulders and my feet. I would never stop the other sports I'm doing, but it's amazing how yoga can pair up with them and just make a whole together. I don't mind the spiritual part of it, I'm very open about other cultures or more precisely I'm very interested to know what belief or what kind of thinking can make others happier and more motivated in the every day life (or on the mat), so that maybe I can try those in my life too or just leave it to them and be glad that it makes them happy and respect it. I never tried to do other types of yoga or the classes of other yoga teachers, and I'm only doing it with your videos. You're very good at pointing out what could go wrong in each position, and it feels like I'm actually participating in real life! For me the most surprising thing about yoga was (and still is) that breathing can be hard! My back and core hurts just by breathing correctly and consciously, because my lungs and ribs are not used to it. It was life changing to realize how important the right breathing is, and how wrong I was doing it before for such a long time! I have a cat since summer, and sometimes she lies behind me, so I can watch her when I stretch, exactly like you did in the beginning of this video with Benji. Sometimes she attacks my hands or feet, or when I'm lying on the floor with closed eyes, she suddenly surprises me with a cold, wet nose or tickly whiskers on my face but maybe that's just her way of sharing the yoga experience with me. :D I'm also watching from Europe (Hungary), but I don't mind the upload schedule, we should just appreciate that it's free and great, and it's amazing and that Adriene puts so much energy, time and effort into this for us. I think if we really want to commit to this, we can also adjust our lives to it, and worst case just do the videos maybe one day later than the correct schedule. Thank you again Adriene and I wish everyone all the best on their yoga journey!
